dial, inner longitudinal","Outer longitudinal, middle circular, inner radial","Outer radial, middle circular, inner longitudinal","Outer longitudinal, middle radial, inner circular"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe ciliary muscle has three distinct layers arranged in a specific order from outer to inner: the \u003Cstrong\u003Eouter longitudinal (meridional) fibres\u003C/strong\u003E attach to the choroid, the \u003Cstrong\u003Emiddle circular fibres\u003C/strong\u003E form a sphincter-like ring, and the \u003Cstrong\u003Einner radial fibres\u003C/strong\u003E extend inward. When these muscle fibres contract, they pull the choroid forward and inward, relaxing tension on the zonular fibres. This allows the elastic lens capsule to assume a more convex shape for near vision (accommodation).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other arrangements listed with \u003Cstrong\u003Eouter radial\u003C/strong\u003E fibres, \u003Cstrong\u003Eouter circular\u003C/strong\u003E fibres, and combinations with different ordering are incorrect and would not facilitate the precise biomechanical action required for accommodation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The ciliary muscle consists of three distinct layers: outer longitudinal (meridional), middle circular, and inner radial fibres.","Contraction of the ciliary muscle relaxes the zonular fibres, allowing the lens to become more convex for near vision (accommodation)."],"references":["Kaphle D, Schmid KL, Davies LN, Suheimat M, Atchison DA. Ciliary Muscle Dimension Changes With Accommodation Vary in Myopia and Emmetropia. Invest Ophthalmol Vis Sci. 2022 Jun 1;63(6):24. doi: 10.1167/iovs.63.6.24. PMID: 35749128; PMCID: PMC9234357.","Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022). The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Probst, L., \u0026 Tsai, J. (2024). Ophthalmology: Clinical and Surgical Principles. CRC Press","Salmon, J. 